Points $A,$ $B,$ and $O$ are marked above for convenience. Because the square was rotated $45^\circ,$ each circular sector (shown in gray) has a central angle of $45^\circ$ and a radius of $AO = \tfrac{\sqrt2}{2}.$ Therefore, put together, they form a semicircle of radius $\tfrac{\sqrt2}{2},$ which has area \[\frac12 \pi \left(\frac{\sqrt2}{2}\right)^2 = \frac{\pi}{4}.\]The four larger triangles (shown in blue) have area equal to half the area of the original square, so they contribute $\tfrac12$ to the overall area. Finally, each of the smaller triangles (shown unshaded) has legs of length $AB = AO - BO = \tfrac{\sqrt2}{2} - \tfrac{1}{2},$ so their total area is \[4 \cdot \frac{1}{2} \left(\frac{\sqrt2}{2} - \frac{1}{2}\right)^2 = \frac{3-2\sqrt2}{2}.\]Thus, the area of the entire given region is \[\frac \pi 4 + \frac12 + \frac{3-2\sqrt2}{2} = \boxed{\frac \pi4 + 2 - \sqrt2}.\] The answer is \frac \pi4 + 2 - \sqrt2.

