Triangles $APB$ and $CQD$ have bases $PB$ and $QD$ of length 1 and heights $AP$ and $CQ$ of length 2, so each has area $$\frac{1}{2}(1)(2)=1.$$Triangles $BRC$ and $DOA$ have bases $BR$ and $DO$ of length 4 and heights $CR$ and $AO$ of length 1, so each has area $$\frac{1}{2}(4)(1)=2.$$Thus, the area of $ABCD$ is $$15 -1-1-2-2=\boxed{9}.$$(Alternatively, we could notice that $ABCD$ is a parallelogram.  Therefore, if we draw the diagonal $AC$, the area is split into two equal pieces.  Dropping a perpendicular from $C$ to $Q$ on the $x$-axis produces a trapezoid $ACQO$ from which only two triangles need to be removed to determine half of the area of $ABCD$.) The answer is 9.

